{
  "id": "019d2422-a671-7ba3-96d1-d34073b875d3",
  "content": "# Hook Migration — 3-Persona Review Synthesis (2026-03-25)\n\n## Senior SWE — Top Findings\n\n1. **Drop the server POST on every hook.** Write JSONL only. On SessionEnd, POST the gzipped file. If you want real-time dashboard visibility, have the server tail the JSONL (inotify). Don't make 200+ HTTP requests per session.\n\n2. **Don't initialize telemetry in CLI hook path.** The 14ms cold start is fast because the CLI doesn't set up tracing subscribers. Adding init_telemetry() adds 3-8ms for spans nobody reads from a 20ms process. Emit structured fields in JSONL, derive telemetry during ingestion.\n\n3. **Drop custom hooks system (YAGNI).** Zero custom hooks exist. Claude Code already supports arbitrary commands in settings.json natively. Building an abstraction layer over an abstraction layer.\n\n4. **Keep matchers in settings.json.** Don't replace per-matcher entries with a single `corvia hooks run` per event type. The current architecture uses Claude Code's native matcher system to avoid running hooks unnecessarily. Moving matcher logic into Rust means every PreToolUse fires the CLI even for tools that don't need it.\n\n5. **Don't add sysinfo/procfs/nix for orphan cleanup.** Use stdlib (/proc reads) and libc::kill. Or better: keep orphan cleanup as bash — it's a temporary workaround.\n\n6. **Add schema versioning** (\"v\": 1) to every JSONL event line from day one.\n\n7. **Fix the `.current-session-id` race condition.** Use session_id from Claude Code's stdin JSON on every invocation. Drop the shared file entirely.\n\n8. **Drop the turn counter file.** Derive turn numbers from JSONL line count during ingestion. Eliminates an entire class of consistency bugs.\n\n## QA — Top 5 Highest-Risk Issues\n\n1. **`.current-session-id` clobber** — concurrent/subagent sessions write to wrong JSONL. Fix: use per-event stdin session_id.\n\n2. **SIGTERM mid-JSONL-write** — partial JSON line makes file unparseable. Fix: atomic write (temp + rename) or length-prefix.\n\n3. **Migration double-firing** — old bash + new Rust hooks both execute. Fix: init-hooks must atomically replace all bash entries.\n\n4. **Turn counter is per-process** — \"in-memory\" claim is wrong, each hook is a separate process. Fix: derive from JSONL.\n\n5. **Custom hook stdout corruption** — custom hook printing to stdout interpreted as Claude Code JSON control response. Fix: capture and isolate stdout.\n\nQA identified 60+ specific test cases across concurrency, error handling, timeouts, state management, platform, server interaction, and custom hooks.\n\n## Product Manager — Key Cuts\n\n1. **Ship 50%:** Dispatcher + session recording + config. Keep everything else as bash via custom hook mechanism.\n\n2. **Cut orphan cleanup migration** — temporary workaround, don't invest in Rust + 3 new crate deps.\n\n3. **Defer real-time server forwarding** — nobody watches the real-time stream. Batch ingest on session end is sufficient.\n\n4. **Add `corvia hooks status`** — debugging UX. Show which hooks are active, last execution, failures.\n\n5. **Add `corvia hooks test`** — dry-run a hook event. Essential for debugging.\n\n6. **Measure baseline first.** Can't claim success without knowing current failure rate of bash hooks.\n\n## Consensus Across All Three Reviewers\n\nAll three agree on:\n- Session recording to Rust is the high-value change\n- Drop .current-session-id shared file (use stdin session_id)\n- Drop turn counter file (derive during ingestion)\n- Add schema versioning to JSONL\n- Phase the migration (don't do everything at once)\n- Keep orphan cleanup as bash (temporary workaround)\n- Don't over-invest in custom hook framework",
  "source_version": "mcp",
